
I wished he had.
Instead, he moved on. The light went out in the hallway. Carmi made a racket in his room, tossing things and dropping other things, but after a while, he went to bed as well.
I wondered how late it was. I wondered how long I stayed up, sitting there, numb from the ice water in my veins.
When I allowed myself to lie down, head against the pillow, I stared out my window. The rain splattered the glass, hypnotic, draining the will from my body, making my eyelids heavier and heavier. No thoughts crossed my mind. I barred them all behind the largest dam I could hold, and I held strong until I finally passed out.



